# System Overview

## Project Description

The Intelligent Dual-Axis Solar PV Tracking System is designed to improve solar energy capture efficiency by dynamically orienting a photovoltaic panel toward the optimal sunlight direction throughout the day.

The project studies and compares two solar tracking approaches:
- Sensor-based reactive tracking
- Predictive azimuth/time-based tracking

---

## System Architecture

### Input Layer
The system receives sunlight information through:
- LDR sensor inputs
- Time & solar position calculations

---

### Control Layer
The Arduino Nano processes:
- Light intensity differences
- Position calculations
- Tracking correction logic

The controller then determines the required panel orientation.

---

### Actuation Layer
Servo/DC motors rotate the solar panel:
- Horizontally (Azimuth Axis)
- Vertically (Elevation Axis)

This enables dual-axis tracking functionality.

---

## Tracking Modes

### Mode 1 — LDR Tracking
The system reacts dynamically to sunlight intensity detected by LDR sensors.

Advantages:
- Real-time response
- Simple implementation
- Low computational requirements

---

### Mode 2 — Time/Azimuth Tracking
The system estimates solar position based on:
- Time of day
- Solar azimuth angle
- Solar elevation angle

Advantages:
- Predictive operation
- Reduced sensor dependency
- Improved tracking consistency

---

